<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>How long can I cellar quality Chardonnay?</h3>
<p>Most Chardonnays reach peak quality within 3-5 years of vintage. Burgundy Grand Crus and top California bottlings can age 10-15 years or longer. Unoaked styles are best consumed within 2-3 years to preserve freshness.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Should I choose oaked or unoaked Chardonnay?</h3>
<p>Your preference for richness versus freshness determines the choice. Oaked versions offer vanilla, toast, and creamy textures. Unoaked styles showcase pure fruit character with crisp acidity. Try both to discover your preference.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What food pairs best with different Chardonnay styles?</h3>
<p>Crisp, unoaked versions complement shellfish, sushi, and goat cheese. Rich, oaked styles match roasted chicken, lobster with butter, and creamy pasta dishes. Medium-bodied wines work with salmon and mushroom preparations.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do I identify quality Chardonnay from the label?</h3>
<p>Look for specific vineyard designations, harvest dates, and alcohol levels below 14.5%. Producer reputation matters more than fancy packaging. French wines show appellation classifications while New World bottles highlight vineyard sites.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Which regions offer the best value for premium Chardonnay?</h3>
<p>Australia consistently delivers quality at reasonable prices. Oregon provides elegant wines comparable to Burgundy at lower costs. Burgundy village wines offer authentic French character without Grand Cru premiums.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the ideal serving temperature for Chardonnay?</h3>
<p>Serve between 50-55°F (10-13°C). Too cold masks flavors and aromatics. Too warm emphasizes alcohol and reduces refreshing qualities. Remove from refrigerator 15-20 minutes before serving for optimal temperature.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can I age inexpensive Chardonnay successfully?</h3>
<p>Most entry-level Chardonnays are designed for immediate consumption. Only bottles with good acidity, balanced oak, and proven producer track records improve with age. Invest aging efforts in premium examples.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do I avoid over-oaked Chardonnay?</h3>
<p>Check tasting notes for descriptors like "vanilla," "butter," or "toast." Excessive oak dominates fruit character. Look for terms like "balanced," "integrated," or "subtle oak influence" to find wines where wood complements rather than overwhelms.</p>
</div>
